le=S\u00f3lo \u00e9xitos: a\u00f1o a a\u00f1o, 1959\u20132002 |language=Spanish |edition=1st |location=Madrid |publisher=[[Sociedad General de Autores y Editores|Fundaci\u00f3n Autor/SGAE]] |page=945 |isbn=84-8048-639-2 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|artist=The Smashing Pumpkins|title=Adore|type=album|award=Gold|relyear=1998|accessdate=March 18, 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=The Smashing Pumpkins|title=Adore|type=album|award=Platinum|relyear=1998|accessdate=March 18, 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n!rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:8em\"| Song\n!colspan=\"7\"| Chart positions\n|-\n!style=\"width:6em;font-size:80%;line-height:1.3;vertical-align:top\"| [[Modern Rock Tracks|US<br />Modern Rock]]<ref name=\"billboardsongs\" /><ref name=\"allmusicsongs\">{{cite web\n  | url = {{Allmusic|class=album|id=r351179|pure_url=yes}}\n  | title = Adore Billboard Singles\n  | publisher = Allmusic.com\n  | accessdate = February 12, 2007\n  }}</ref>\n!style=\"width:6em;font-size:80%;line-height:1.3;vertical-align:top\"| [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|US<br />Mainstream Rock]]<ref name=\"billboardsongs\" /><ref name=\"allmusicsongs\" />\n!style=\"width:6em;font-size:80%;line-height:1.3;vertical-align:top\"| [[Canadian Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"allmusicsongs\" />\n!style=\"width:6em;font-size:80%;line-height:1.3;vertical-align:top\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK<br />Singles Chart]]<ref name=\"everyhit\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.everyhit.com/ \n |title=EveryHit.com \n |accessdate=February 16, 2007 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070217183242/http://www.everyhit.com/ \n |archivedate=February 17, 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n!style=\"width:6em;font-size:80%;line-height:1.3;vertical-align:top\"| [[Australian Singles Chart]]<ref>{{cite web\n  | url = http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=The+Smashing+Pumpkins&titel=Ava+Adore&cat=s\n  | title = THE SMASHING PUMPKINS\u2014AVA ADORE (SINGLE) (49344)\n  | publisher = Australian-charts.com\n  | accessdate = February 16, 2007\n  }}</ref>\n!style=\"width:6em;font-size:80%;line-height:1.3;vertical-align:top\"| [[The Billboard Hot 100|US<br />Hot 100]]<ref name=\"billboardsongs\" /><ref name=\"allmusicsongs\" />\n!style=\"width:6em;font-size:80%;line-height:1.3;vertical-align:top\"| [[Adult Top 40|US<br />Adult Top 40]]<ref name=\"allmusicsongs\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1998\n| \"[[Ava Adore]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 8\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 9\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 11\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 19\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 42\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|&nbsp;\u2014\n|-\n| \"[[Perfect (The Smashing Pumpkins song)|Perfect]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 33\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 13\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 24\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 56\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 54\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 31\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{The Smashing Pumpkins}}\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adore (Album)}}\n[[Category:1998 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Billy Corgan]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Brad Wood]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Flood (producer)]]\n[[Category:The Smashing Pumpkins albums]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records albums]]\n[[Category:Electronica albums by American artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Adore\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[The Smashing Pumpkins]]\n| cover      = SmashingPumpkins-Adore.jpg\n| alt        = A black-and-white photo of a Caucasian woman leaning forward while holding the ends of a flowing black dress. In the corner, \"Adore\" is displayed in white handwriting.\n| released   = {{start date|1998|6|2|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = June 1997&nbsp;\u2013 March 1998\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Sunset Sound Recorders|Sunset Sound]], The Village Recorder, Chicago Recording Company & various studios\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Electronic rock]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5944947/smashing-pumpkins-to-release-pair-of-epic-albums-in-2015 | title=Smashing Pumpkins to Release Pair of 'Epic' Albums in 2015 | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date=March 25, 2014 | accessdate=November 23, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[gothic rock]]<ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/smashing-pumpkins-machina-the-machines-of-god | title=Smashing Pumpkins \u2013 Machina: The Machines of God | magazine=[[Slant Magazine]] | date=April 7, 2001 | accessdate=November 23, 2015 | author=Cinquemani, Sal}}</ref>\n* [[art rock]]<ref name=\"AMGreview\" />\n* [[synth-pop]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/news/39248-listen-passion-pit-cover-smashing-pumpkins-remix-katy-perry/ | title=Listen: Passion Pit Cover Smashing Pumpkins, Remix Katy Perry | publisher=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]] | date=June 23, 2010 | accessdate=November 26, 2015 | author=Breihan, Tom}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=73|s=25}}\n| label      = [[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Billy Corgan]]\n* [[Flood (producer)|Flood]]\n* [[Brad Wood]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[The Aeroplane Flies High]]\n| prev_year  = 1996\n| next_title = [[Machina/The Machines of God]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Adore\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Ava Adore]]\n | single1date = May 18, 1998\n | single2     = [[Perfect (The Smashing Pumpkins song)|Perfect]]\n | single2date = September 7, 1998\n}}\n{{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternate cover\n | type    = album\n | cover   = The_Smashing_Pumpkins_-_Adore_reissue_cover.jpg\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption = Vinyl cover/2014 reissue cover\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Adore''''' is the fourth studio album by the American [[alternative rock]] band [[The Smashing Pumpkins]], released in June 1998 by [[Virgin Records]]. After the multi-platinum success of ''[[Mellon Collie and the Infinite Sadness]]'' and a subsequent yearlong world tour, follow-up ''Adore'' was considered \"one of the most anticipated albums of 1998\" by MTV.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/#/news/articles/1434206/19980428/story.jhtml |title=Smashing Pumpkins Set Release Date, Track Listing For \"Adore\" |publisher=MTV |date=April 28, 1998 |accessdate=February 13, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070212234709/http://www.mtv.com/#/music/artist/kudai/artist.jhtml| archivedate=February 12, 2007| url-status= live}}</ref> Recording the album proved to be a challenge as the band members struggled with lingering interpersonal problems and musical uncertainty in the wake of three increasingly successful [[rock music|rock]] albums and the departure of drummer [[Jimmy Chamberlin]].<ref>The primary source on the recording climate is a three-part blog written by Billy Corgan in 2005, all three of which are referenced extensively in the body of this article.</ref> Frontman [[Billy Corgan]] would later characterize ''Adore'' as \"a band falling apart\".<ref>Interview: Billy Corgan. ''INsite Magazine''. May 14, 2000.</ref> Corgan has also mentioned he was going through a divorce while recording the album.\n\nThe result was a much more subdued and [[electronica]]-tinged sound that [[Greg Kot]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine called \"a complete break with the past\".<ref name=\"rolling stone review\">{{cite magazine |author=Kot, Greg |authorlink=Greg Kot |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/adore-19980518 |title=Adore |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=May 18, 1998 |accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref> The album divided the fan base and sold only a fraction of the previous two albums. However, the album was well received by critics, and became the third straight Pumpkins album to be nominated for the [[41st Annual Grammy Awards|Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Alternative Music Album|Best Alternative Music Performance]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/specials/1999/grammys/bigpicture.html |title=41st annual Grammy nominees and winners |publisher=[[CNN.com]] |date=February 24, 1999 |accessdate=February 11, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061222042453/http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/specials/1999/grammys/bigpicture.html |archivedate=December 22, 2006}}</ref> and has gained a cult following. A remastered and expanded version of the album was released on CD and vinyl in September 2014 as a part of the band's project to reissue their back catalogue from 1991\u20132000.\n\n== Background ==\nThe Smashing Pumpkins had cemented their place as a cultural force with the multi-platinum ''Mellon Collie and the Infinite Sadness''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 100 Albums |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=2&table=tblTop100&action= |accessdate=August 6, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725044825/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=2&table=tblTop100&action= |archivedate=July 25, 2013  }}</ref> Feeling the limitations of their guitar-driven hard rock sound, the band had started to branch out during the making of ''Mellon Collie'', and, after the chart-topping success of the electronic-leaning \"[[1979 (song)|1979]]\",<ref name=\"billboardsongs\">{{cite magazine |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=smashing pumpkins|chart=all}} |title=The Smashing Pumpkins Artist Chart History |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |accessdate=February 12, 2007}}</ref> the band zeroed in on electronica.<ref>Graff, Gary. \"Smashing Pumpkins\u2014Rave of the Future\", ''Guitar World''. December 1996.</ref>\nAs the sprawling and massively successful ''Infinite Sadness'' tour wound down, Billy Corgan found himself facing many difficult issues, including musical burnout, the absence of his \"best friend and musical soul mate in the band\" Jimmy Chamberlin, the end of his marriage, and the death of his mother to cancer.<ref name=\"corgan a\">Corgan, Billy.  \"[http://billycorgan.livejournal.com/11418.html Starcrossed, and subsequently, a door is opened (1997)]\".  ''The Confessions of Billy Corgan''.  April 12, 2005.</ref>\n\nDuring this period, the band released two new singles on movie soundtracks\u2014\"[[Eye (song)|Eye]]\" and \"[[The End Is the Beginning Is the End]]\". Both songs incorporated electronic elements, yet retained the [[hard rock]] elements of the band's previous material; one reviewer called the two singles \"balls-out, full-energy chargers\" and wrote off the Pumpkins' previous remarks that the upcoming album would \"rock\" less.<ref name=\"pfork\" /> However, the new album material Corgan was writing consisted mainly of simple acoustic songs.<ref name=\"corgan a\"/> Corgan, [[James Iha]], [[D'arcy Wretzky]], and [[Matt Walker (drummer)|Matt Walker]] spent a few days in the studio in February 1997 laying down demos mostly as live takes, and the band hoped to quickly record an entire album in such a manner.<ref name=\"corgan a\"/> Corgan, hoping to maintain the band's [[progressive rock]]-inspired experimentation, soon had second thoughts about this approach and began envisioning a hybrid of [[folk rock]] and electronica that was at once \"ancient\" and \"futuristic\".<ref name=\"corgan a\"/>\n\n== Recording ==\nThe Smashing Pumpkins started demoing in February 1997 and recorded 30 songs for the album which, at one point, looked set to be a double album. The band subsequently cut the number of tracks on the album to 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/smashing-pumpkins/63 |title=NME News PUMPKINS REVEAL DETAILS OF LENGTHY 'ADORE' SESSIONS |date=January 24, 1998 |publisher=Nme.com |accessdate=October 2, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006093635/http://www.nme.com/news/smashing-pumpkins/63 |archivedate=October 6, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAfter playing several festival dates in summer 1997, the band began working at a variety of Chicago studios with producer [[Brad Wood]]\u2014with whom Corgan previously had worked in the early 1990s.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/smashingpumpkins/articles/story/5929771/pumpkins_to_record_with_brad_wood |title=Pumpkins To Record With Brad Wood |magazine=Rollingstone.com |date=July 4, 1997 |accessdate=February 18, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002092147/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/smashingpumpkins/articles/story/5929771/pumpkins_to_record_with_brad_wood |archivedate=October 2, 2007 }}</ref> While ''Mellon Collie'' had mostly been recorded with the full participation of all the band members, the band dynamics during the new sessions soon muddled as Corgan, uninspired by his bandmates, worked mostly alone.<ref name=\"corgan a\"/> Wood, too, was leaving Corgan unsatisfied, so, after six weeks in Chicago, the band\u2014minus Wood and Matt Walker\u2014relocated to Los Angeles and started work at [[Sunset Sound]], with Corgan now the de facto producer.<ref name=\"corgan a\"/><ref name=\"Starla\">{{cite web |url=http://www.starla.org/chrono/1998.html |author=Bansal, Sachin |title=The Smashing Pumpkins Chronology: The Adore Era: 1998 |publisher=Starla.com |accessdate=February 12, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070203174536/http://www.starla.org/chrono/1998.html| archivedate=February 3, 2007| url-status= live}}</ref>\n[[File:Matt Cameron SG 2013.jpg|alt=|thumb|Due to Jimmy Chamberlin being fired from The Smashing Pumpkins, [[Soundgarden]] drummer [[Matt Cameron]] was one of several percussionists brought into the studio to record with the band]]\nThe band rented a house, and hoped living communally would foster good relations and a happier recording environment.<ref name=\"corgan b\">Corgan, Billy. \"[http://billycorgan.livejournal.com/11818.html Way Out in Outpost Canyon]\". ''The Confessions of Billy Corgan''. April 13, 2005.</ref> According to Corgan, Iha refused to live in the house and rarely visited.<ref name=\"corgan b\"/> The recording sessions continued to be slow-moving and heavily technical.<ref name=\"corgan c\">Corgan, Billy. \"[http://billycorgan.livejournal.com/12575.html Coming Down the Mountain]\". ''The Confessions of Billy Corgan''. April 14, 2005.</ref> In the absence of a drummer, the band used a [[drum machine]] as it had in its earliest incarnation.<ref name=\"corgan b\"/> The band also enlisted [[Joey Waronker]], of [[Beck]]'s band, and [[Matt Cameron]], of [[Soundgarden]] and [[Pearl Jam]], for a few songs each.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcdsp.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=72&Itemid=34 |title=Joey Waronker |publisher=McDSP.com\n| accessdate = February 18, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/smashingpumpkins/articles/story/5927993/matt_cameron_hanging_with_the_pumpkins |title=Matt Cameron Hanging With The Pumpkins? |magazine=Rollingstone.com |date=December 9, 1997 |accessdate=February 18, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070602165834/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/smashingpumpkins/articles/story/5927993/matt_cameron_hanging_with_the_pumpkins |archivedate=June 2, 2007  }}</ref> [[Bon Harris]] of [[Nitzer Ebb]] contributed electronic sequencing and sounds to eight album tracks, with the band giving him mostly free rein.<ref>Hindin, Seth.  JamTV News.  February 17, 1998.</ref>\n\nAt the behest of the band's management, [[Rick Rubin]] was brought in to produce one song, \"Let Me Give the World to You\", but the song was left off the album, later to be re-recorded for ''[[Machina II/The Friends & Enemies of Modern Music]]''.<ref name=\"nme\">{{cite web\n |author=''NME'' staff \n |title=Pumpkins Reveal Details of Lengthy ''Adore'' Sessions \n |publisher=[[NME]] \n |url=http://www.nme.com/news/smashing-pumpkins/63 \n |date=January 24, 1998 \n |accessdate=February 13, 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006093635/http://www.nme.com/news/smashing-pumpkins/63 \n |archivedate=October 6, 2014 \n}}</ref> With around thirty songs recorded, Corgan began to see an end, and enlisted ''Mellon Collie'' co-producer [[Flood (producer)|Flood]] to help finish the recording, pull the album together, and mix the songs.<ref name=\"corgan c\"/>\n\nArt direction for the album is credited to Frank Olinsky, Billy Corgan, and Corgan's then-girlfriend and frequent collaborator [[Yelena Yemchuk]]. The artwork for the album and its singles consisted almost entirely of black-and-white photographs shot by Yemchuk, many of which featured model [[Amy Wesson]].<ref name=\"booklet\" />\n\n=== Music ===\nCorgan was deliberately setting out to widen his band's sound and message, explaining that he was not \"talking to teenagers anymore. I'm talking to everyone now. It's a wider dialogue. I'm talking to people who are older than me and younger than me, and our generation as well.\"<ref name=\"Starla\" /> He said much of the record was \"an attempt to go back to what's important at a musical core and build it outward\".<ref>Lanham, Tom. \"This One Goes Out to the One I Love\". ''CMJ NEW Music Monthly''. August 1998.</ref> He would later reflect that he was \"stuck on the idea that [he] needed to prove [he] was an artist, which is the [[death knell]] of any artist\".<ref name=\"mojo12\">Alexander, Phil. ''Interview with Billy Corgan''.  [[Mojo (magazine)|''Mojo'']].  February 2012.</ref>\n\n[[Distortion (music)|Distorted]] guitars and live drums, the previous hallmarks of the Pumpkins sound, took a back seat in a sonic palette that included much more synthesizers, [[drum programming]], [[acoustic guitar]], and piano.<ref name=\"rolling stone review\" /> At least five songs on the album are driven chiefly by piano.<ref name=\"rolling stone review\" />\n\n\"Tear\" was written for the ''[[Lost Highway (film)|Lost Highway]]'' soundtrack, but was rejected by [[David Lynch]] in favor of \"[[Eye (song)|Eye]]\".<ref>{{cite video |people=Justin Coloma (director), Amy Kettenburg (producer/interviewer) |date=November 4, 2009 |title=DLF.TV Visits Billy Corgan of the Smashing Pumpkins |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IjYAqyZiObM |publisher=David Lynch Foundation}}</ref> \"Pug\" was originally recorded as a \"[[minor key]] [[blues music|blues]] death [[march (music)|march]]\" with drums by Matt Cameron, while the album version uses drum programming.<ref name=\"nme\"/> The only song on the album to feature Cameron, \"For Martha\", is a tribute to Corgan's mother that was primarily recorded as one live take.<ref name=\"corgan c\"/>\n\nApart from being the first album without Jimmy Chamberlin, ''Adore'' was the first album to not include writing contributions from James Iha,<ref name=\"booklet\">(1998) Album notes for ''Adore'' by The Smashing Pumpkins, [CD booklet]. Beverly Hills: Virgin America.</ref> who was concurrently working on his solo album ''[[Let It Come Down (James Iha album)|Let It Come Down]]''. However, he did contribute the track \"Summer\" to the \"[[Perfect (The Smashing Pumpkins song)|Perfect]]\" single.<ref name=\"booklet\"/>\n\n== Promotion and release ==\n{{Listen\n|filename     = ava_adore.ogg\n|title        = \"Ava Adore\"\n|description  = Sample of \"Ava Adore\", the first single from ''Adore'' (1998), which emphasizes the band's new electronic music-based sound via the use of drum machines and effects.\n}}\n\nThe lead-up to ''Adore'' was marked by conflicting statements as to the album's sound\u2014Corgan initially said the band was heading in the direction of the heavy-metal-guitar-and-electronic music-driven \"The End Is the Beginning Is the End\" in summer 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/gallery/s/wirsmashing970502.html |title=\"The Week in Rock for May 2, 1997\" |accessdate=September 23, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19970614024604/http://www.mtv.com/news/gallery/s/wirsmashing970502.html |archivedate=June 14, 1997 |work=Mtv Online}}</ref> while the band's management reported the album would be all-acoustic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/1158/19970909/smashing_pumpkins.jhtml |author=Kaufman, Gil |title=News Flash: Smashing Pumpkins Next LP All Acoustic |publisher=VH1.com |date=September 10, 1997 |accessdate=February 13, 2007}}</ref> In early 1998, Corgan called the sound \"arcane night music\",<ref>{{cite web|author=Kaufman, Gil |title=Pumpkins Recording Album of \"Arcane Night Music\" |publisher=Addicted to Noise/JamesIha.org |url=http://jamesiha.org/newsdatabase.php?id=1534 |date=January 14, 1998 |accessdate=February 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070802125549/http://www.jamesiha.org/newsdatabase.php?id=1534 |archivedate=August 2, 2007  }}</ref> elaborating, \"The people that say it's acoustic will be wrong. The people that say it's electronic will be wrong. The people that say it's a Pumpkins record will be wrong. I will try to make something that is indescribable\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Billy Corgan Says Fans May Be Surprised By Next Pumpkin's LP |publisher=MTV |url=http://www.mtv.com/#/news/articles/1434210/19980226/smashing_pumpkins.jhtml\n| date=February 26, 1998 |accessdate=February 13, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070212234709/http://www.mtv.com/#/music/artist/kudai/artist.jhtml| archivedate=February 12, 2007| url-status= live}}</ref> Further complicating the situation was the record label's initial insistence to use the [[Rick Rubin]] produced, upbeat, poppy song \"[[Let Me Give the World to You]]\" as the album's [[lead single]], something Corgan strongly objected to, fearing it would give listeners the wrong first impression of the album.<ref name=\"radio.com\"/> Corgan had to drop the song off the track list altogether to avoid using it as a single.<ref name=\"radio.com\">[http://radio.com/2014/09/22/billy-corgan-smashing-pumpkins-adore-interview/ Billy Corgan on \u2018Adore,\u2019 His \u201990s Self and the Final Days of Alt-Rock \u00ab Radio.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826010202/http://radio.com/2014/09/22/billy-corgan-smashing-pumpkins-adore-interview/ |date=August 26, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n''Adore'' was released on June 1, 1998, in most of the world, the same day the video for first single \"[[Ava Adore]]\" premiered. The album booklet and music video showcased the band's new [[Gothic fashion|gothic]] look. The second single, \"Perfect\", was also accompanied by a music video, which debuted on August 16.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/#/news/articles/1434194/19980730/story.jhtml |title=Smashing Pumpkins Shoot \"Perfect\" Video, Mull Recording Future |publisher=MTV |date=July 30, 1998 |accessdate=February 13, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070212234709/http://www.mtv.com/#/music/artist/kudai/artist.jhtml| archivedate=February 12, 2007| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n== Touring ==\nAfter the release of ''Adore'', the band embarked on a scaled-back 14-show world tour entitled ''An Evening with The Smashing Pumpkins'' to support ''Adore''.<ref name=\"spfc 1998\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spfc.org/tours/date.html?year=1998\n| title=spfc.org: tour history\u2014dates (1998) |publisher=The Smashing Pumpkins Fan Collaborative |accessdate=August 18, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070904004148/http://www.spfc.org/tours/date.html?year=1998| archivedate=September 4, 2007| url-status= live}}</ref> Abroad, the Pumpkins played at what had been called an \"eclectic mix of interesting venues\",<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/pumpkins-premiere-songs-from-adore-19980505 |title=Pumpkins Premiere Songs From \"Adore\" |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=May 5, 1998 |accessdate=April 3, 2007}}</ref> among them the rooftop of a FNAC record store in Paris, France,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spfc.org/tours/date.html?tour_id=624 |title=1998-06-04, FNAC Rooftop |publisher=spfc.org |accessdate=February 18, 2007}}</ref> in the botanic gardens of [[Brussels]], Belgium,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.songkick.com/concerts/639704-smashing-pumpkins-at-botanique |title=1998-05-28, Smashing Pumpkins, Botanique |accessdate=September 8, 2011}}</ref> at the [[Cannes Film Festival]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spfc.org/tours/date.html?tour_id=612 |title=1998-05-18, Palais des Festivals et des Congr\u00e8s |publisher=spfc.org |accessdate=October 29, 2014}}</ref> and at an International Shipping Harbor in Sydney, Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spfc.org/tours/date.html?tour_id=647 |title=1998-06-19, Overseas Passenger Terminal|publisher=spfc.org |accessdate=October 29, 2014}}</ref> In the United States, the Pumpkins donated 100% of their ticket profits to local charities<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vh1.com/artists/news/510299/19981221/smashing_pumpkins.jhtml |title='98's Best: Teen Murderer Flees Jail To Catch Pumpkins Show |publisher=[[VH1]] |accessdate=July 16, 2007}}</ref> (yet one stop on the tour, Minneapolis, was a free concert and underestimated the attendance of the show).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1434204/19980507/smashing_pumpkins.jhtml |title=Smashing Pumpkins To Play Free Minneapolis Show |publisher=Mtv.com |date=May 7, 1998 |accessdate=December 23, 2010}}</ref> In the end, the Pumpkins, with the help of their fans, raised over $2.8&nbsp;million in this manner.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1434191/09221998/smashing_pumpkins.jhtml |title=Smashing Pumpkins Raise Over $2.8&nbsp;Million on Charity Tour |author=MTV News staff |publisher=MTV |date=September 22, 1998 |accessdate=February 11, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509173841/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1434191/09221998/smashing_pumpkins.jhtml |archivedate=May 9, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe lineup was the most expansive yet, including former [[John Mellencamp]] and [[Melissa Etheridge]] drummer [[Kenny Aronoff]],<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Kenny Aronoff\u2014News Archive 1998 \n |publisher=Kennyaronoff.com \n |url=http://www.kennyaronoff.com/news/archive1998.php \n |accessdate=February 16, 2007 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070209140228/http://www.kennyaronoff.com/news/archive1998.php \n |archivedate=February 9, 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> percussionists Dan Morris and [[Stephen Hodges]], and [[David Bowie]] pianist [[Mike Garson]].<ref>{{cite web\n |title=NEWS\u2014NEW TOUR DATES! \n |publisher=[[Virgin Records]] \n |url=http://www.virginrecords.com/xspx/pumpkinsnews.html \n |accessdate=February 11, 2007 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212203003/http://www.virginrecords.com/xspx/pumpkinsnews.html \n |archivedate=February 12, 2007 \n |url-status=dead\n}}</ref> Violinist [[Lisa Germano]] was also set to appear,<ref>{{cite web|title=SMASHING PUMPKINS WANNA BE 'ADORE-D' |publisher=[[NME]] |url=http://www.nme.com/news/smashing-pumpkins/202 |date=April 5, 1998 |accessdate=February 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118130547/http://www.nme.com/news/smashing-pumpkins/202 |archivedate=January 18, 2012 }}</ref> but did not ultimately appear in the touring line-up. The set was mainly ''Adore'' material, with only a handful of reworked ''Mellon Collie'' songs and no songs from prior to 1995, eliminating many of their radio hits and fan favorites,<ref name=\"spfc 1998\"/> with the exception of some shows performed in South American countries like Brazil and Chile, where they played for the first time, so they included old hits like \"Today\" and \"Disarm\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spfc.org/tours/date.html?tour_id=682|title=spfc.org : tour history - dates : 1998-08-16|website=www.spfc.org|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spfc.org/tours/date.html?tour_id=683|title=spfc.org : tour history - dates : 1998-08-19|website=www.spfc.org|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn retrospect, Corgan regretted the decision to hire the two percussionists to play alongside Aronoff, instead of having the drummer play along with loops from the album. \"That drove Kenny up the wall because Kenny has perfect time and one guy played on top and the other behind. I remember Kenny saying, 'I feel like I'm tripping on LSD' because he kept hearing things that were not in time, and it drove him crazy,\" said Corgan in the ''Adore'' reissue liner notes. Performing with Garson was also challenging because, according to Corgan, \"he made a decision 40 years ago that he would live in the intuitive flow of what he was feeling, so he literally cannot play the same thing twice. So we'd have gigs where he'd have that same magic as on ''[[Aladdin Sane]]'' and the next night he'd come and play the extreme opposite style\u2014like [[honkytonk]]. I really respect Mike, but to play with him was always challenging; precisely because he is such a supreme musician.\"<ref>[[David Wild|Wild, David]]. \"'Adore' of Perceptions\", ''Adore'' reissue liner notes, 2014. Retrieved on September 3, 2015.</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Album reviews\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"AMGreview\">{{cite web |author=Erlewine, Stephen Thomas |authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/adore-mw0000035035 |title=Adore \u2013 The Smashing Pumpkins |website=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=February 11, 2007}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref>{{cite news |author=DeRogatis, Jim |authorlink=Jim DeRogatis |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4447747.html |title=Pumpkins' best yet |work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=June 2, 1998 |accessdate=October 17, 2016 |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181119071325/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4447747.html |archive-date=November 19, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = B+<ref name=\"ewReview\">{{cite journal |author=Browne, David |authorlink=David Browne (journalist) |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,283458,00.html |title=Small Bang Theory |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=June 5, 1998 |accessdate=April 3, 2007}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite news |author=Sweeting, Adam |title=Smashing hits |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=May 29, 1998}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref>{{cite news |author=Cromelin, Richard |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/may/31/entertainment/ca-54991 |title=The Smashing Pumpkins 'Adore' Virgin |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=May 31, 1998 |accessdate=October 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019004320/http://articles.latimes.com/1998/may/31/entertainment/ca-54991 |archive-date=October 19, 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev6Score = 5/10<ref>{{cite journal |author=Sutherland, Steve |url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000822reviews.html |title=The Smashing Pumpkins \u2013 Adore |work=[[NME]] |date=May 30, 1998 |accessdate=October 17, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000817174057/http://www.nme.com/reviews/reviews/19980101000822reviews.html |archive-date=August 17, 2000 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7Score = 8.1/10<ref name=\"pfork\"/>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"rolling stone review\" />\n| rev9 = ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]''\n| rev9Score = 3/5<ref>{{cite journal |author=Lawrence, Eddy |title=The Smashing Pumpkins: Adore |work=[[Select (magazine)|Select]] |issue=97 |date=July 1998 |pages=78\u201379}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev10Score = 5/10<ref>{{cite journal |author=Wolk, Douglas |authorlink=Douglas Wolk |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OStTbPbsrNgC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA121 |title=The Smashing Pumpkins: Adore |volume=14 |issue=7 |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=July 1998 |accessdate=October 17, 2016 |page=121}}</ref>\n}}\n\nCritical reception to ''Adore'' was generally positive. Greg Kot of ''Rolling Stone'' magazine regarded ''Adore'' as \"the most intimate album the Pumpkins have ever made and also the prettiest, a parade of swooning melodies and gentle, unfolding nocturnes\".<ref name=\"rolling stone review\" /> Ryan Schreiber of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' described the album as \"the Pumpkins' best offering since ''Siamese Dream''\".<ref name=\"pfork\">{{cite web |author=Schreiber, Ryan |url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/s/smashing-pumpkins/adore.shtml |title=Smashing Pumpkins: Adore |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=June 1, 1998 |accessdate=June 12, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020803081256/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/record-reviews/s/smashing-pumpkins/adore.shtml |archivedate=August 3, 2002}}</ref> Stephen Thomas Erlewine of [[AllMusic]] described ''Adore'' as \"a hushed, elegiac album that sounds curiously out of time\".<ref name=\"AMGreview\"/> ''Adore'' was considered one of \"an inspiring range of 25 classic alternative American albums\" by ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/omm/story/0,,1200899,00.html |title=Win 25 Classic Grunge Albums |newspaper=[[The Observer]] |date=April 25, 2004 |accessdate=March 24, 2007 |location=London}}</ref> The lyrics received particular praise from critics\u2014[[Jim DeRogatis]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', who in 1993 had criticized Corgan's lyrics as \"too often sound[ing] like sophomoric poetry\",<ref>DeRogatis, Jim. ''Milk It!: Collected Musings on the Alternative Music Explosion of the 90's''. Cambridge: Da Capo, 2003. P. 80. {{ISBN|0-306-81271-1}}</ref> said Corgan \"took a big leap forward as a lyricist\" starting with ''Adore''.<ref>DeRogatis, p. 88</ref> Schreiber, who criticized ''Mellon Collie'' as \"lyrical rock-bottom\",<ref>{{cite web |author=Schreiber, Ryan |url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/21809-mellon-collie-and-the-infinite-sadness |title=Smashing Pumpkins: Mellon Collie and the Infinite Sadness |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=January 1, 1996 |accessdate=April 3, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070430194153/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/record_review/21809-mellon-collie-and-the-infinite-sadness| archivedate=April 30, 2007| url-status=dead}}</ref> called ''Adore''{{'}}s lyrics \"poetic\", particularly singling out \"To Sheila\".<ref name=\"pfork\" /> Greg Kot emphasized the \"oblique, private longings, and weighty, sometimes awkward conceits\" in the lyrics,<ref name=\"rolling stone review\" /> while David Browne of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' called them \"unsettled and unsettling\".<ref name=\"ewReview\"/> The contributions of Wretzky and Iha also received praise, with Kot noting that \"Iha's quirky guitar accents and Wretzky's unflashy resolve [...] give ''Adore'' a warmth and camaraderie no other Pumpkins album can match.\"<ref name=\"seeds\">Kot, Greg. \"Pumpkin Seeds\", ''Guitar World''. January 2002.</ref>\n\nDespite this, public reception to ''Adore'' was lukewarm.<ref>{{cite magazine |author=Fricke, David |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/smashingpumpkins/articles/story/5921548/when_billy_corgan_speaks |title=When Billy Corgan Speaks&nbsp;... |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=December 29, 1998 |accessdate=February 11, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070127051909/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/smashingpumpkins/articles/story/5921548/when_billy_corgan_speaks| archivedate=January 27, 2007| url-status= dead}}</ref> ''Adore'' entered the ''Billboard'' album charts at number two with 174,000 units of the album sold,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ca.music.yahoo.com/read/news/12040652 |title=Master P Beats Pumpkins Debut |author=Haring Bruce |publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]] |date=June 12, 1998 |accessdate=October 9, 2007}}</ref> and was certified [[Music recording sales certification|platinum]] by the [[RIAA]] five weeks later,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |title=Gold and Platinum Database Search |accessdate=February 12, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701082704/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |archivedate=July 1, 2007 }}</ref> but the album soon departed the charts, leaving ''Adore'' far short of the sales figures of its predecessors. Two additional promotional singles, \"[[Crestfallen]]\" and \"To Sheila\", were released to radio stations but failed to gain traction and were never released as commercial singles.<ref name=\"Starla\" />\nAs of May 2005, ''Adore'' has sold 1.1&nbsp;million units in the U.S., and at least three times as many copies worldwide.<ref name=\"seeds\" />\n\nCorgan blamed himself for the record's reception with the public, saying he \"made the mistake of telling people it was a techno record\" and that if he \"would have told everyone ''Adore'' was the Pumpkins' acoustic album we would have never had the problems that we had\".<ref>{{cite video |people=Hedblade, Jock (Director) |date=January 31, 2000 |title=Smashing Pumpkins: Full Circle |publisher=Fox Television Network |location=Chicago, Illinois}}</ref> Corgan wrote on the band's website that the album's title was \"misunderstood\" and \"a joke that no one ever got\", explaining that ''Adore'' was meant as a play on \"A Door\", meaning the album would offer a new entrance to the band's career.<ref>\"[http://www.smashingpumpkinsnexus.com/#!ADORE-UPDATE-FROM-BILLY-CORGAN-AND-INFO-ON-HOW-TO-PRE-ORDER-AUTOGRAPHED-COPIES-AT-MADAMEZUZUSCOM-/c7ba/59DF2946-559F-4200-B532-C5BCB6F962C8 The Panopticon]\". July 16, 2014.</ref> In 2005, Corgan would call the making of the album \"one of the most painful experiences of my life\".<ref name=\"corgan b\"/>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = [[Billy Corgan]]\n| title1 = To Sheila \n| length1 = 4:46\n| title2 = [[Ava Adore]]\n| length2 = 4:21\n| title3 = [[Perfect (Smashing Pumpkins song)|Perfect]]\n| length3 = 3:23\n| title4 = Daphne Descends \n| length4 = 4:39\n| title5 = Once Upon a Time\n| length5 = 4:06\n| title6 = Tear\n| length6 = 5:53\n| title7 = [[Crestfallen]]\n| length7 = 4:09\n| title8 = Appels + Oranjes \n| length8 = 3:35\n| title9 = Pug\n| length9 = 4:47\n| title10 = The Tale of Dusty and Pistol Pete\n| length10 = 4:35\n| title11 = Annie-Dog\n| length11 = 3:38\n| title12 = Shame\n| length12 = 6:40\n| title13 = Behold! The Night Mare\n| length13 = 5:13\n| title14 = For Martha\n| length14 = 8:18\n| title15 = Blank Page\n| length15 = 4:58\n| title16 = 17\n| note16 = not on vinyl pressings\n| length16 = 0:17\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = Japanese edition bonus track\n| title16 = Once in a While\n| note16 = \"17\" moves to track 17\n| length16 = 3:33\n}}\n\n=== 2014 CD/DVD reissue ===\nAs part of Virgin/Universal Music's reissue campaign, a special edition of the album was released on September 23, 2014.<ref name=pressrelease>{{cite web |url=http://www.smashingpumpkinsnexus.com/#!ADORE-UPDATE-FROM-BILLY-CORGAN-AND-INFO-ON-HOW-TO-PRE-ORDER-AUTOGRAPHED-COPIES-AT-MADAMEZUZUSCOM-/c7ba/59DF2946-559F-4200-B532-C5BCB6F962C8 |title=The Official Smashing Pumpkins Website \u2013 Adore Update from Billy Corgan |publisher=Smashingpumpkinsnexis.com |accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref><ref name=amazon_listing>{{cite web|title=Adore (Super Deluxe Edition 6CD/1DVD)|url=https://www.amazon.com/Adore-Super-Deluxe-6CD-1DVD/dp/B00LXLQNP6/ref=tmm_acd_title_0?_encoding=UTF8&sr=&qid=1405430643|website=[[Amazon.com]]|accessdate=September 23, 2014}}</ref> The release consists of the original album remastered and 91 bonus tracks of previously unreleased material, demos and alternate versions of ''Adore''-era songs, and was released in five formats; the physical box set containing all 107 tracks, the [[Music download|digital]] deluxe edition containing 74 of the bonus tracks, as well as single disc [[compact disc|CD]] and double-[[Gramophone record|LP]] versions containing only the stereo remaster of the album.<ref name=pressrelease /> The digital version of the reissue was released on October 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/ie/album/adore-super-deluxe/id911645241 |title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Adore (Super Deluxe) by Smashing Pumpkins |publisher=[[iTunes Store]] |accessdate=September 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe actual ''Adore'' album was remastered by [[Bob Ludwig]]. The entire set includes session outtakes and a mono version of the album, with Corgan saying the new mixes contain \"elements from the original sessions that were stored digitally, but never used; such as some of the work done by [[Bon Harris]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/smashing-pumpkins-reissue-adore-with-three-discs-of-unreleased-music-20140410#ixzz2z6NQ7VQn |title=Smashing Pumpkins Reissue 'Adore' With Three Discs of Unreleased Music |first=Jon |last=Blistein |work=[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]] |date=April 10, 2014 |accessdate=April 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe package also includes a DVD consisting of footage of the band's show from August 4, 1998, at the Fox Theater in Atlanta, Georgia.<ref name=pressrelease />\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = 2014 Reissue CD 1: ''Adore'' Stereo Remastered\n| title1 = To Sheila \n| length1 = 4:40\n| title2 = Ava Adore\n| length2 = 4:30\n| title3 = Perfect\n| length3 = 3:22\n| title4 = Daphne Descends \n| length4 = 4:39\n| title5 = Once Upon a Time\n| length5 = 4:04\n| title6 = Tear\n| length6 = 5:52\n| 